Stock Trading App Tutorial Part 4-6

Part 4: Scheduled Jobs

  • Want to keep database up to date with scheduled task to run table population file.
  • Will be useful when snapshotting price data, to build up backtesting data over time.
  • Acts as basis for automating trade execution (e.g. Script on schedule of every 5 min).
  • Automated with cron for OSX and Linux, Windows Task Scheduler for Windows.
    • Preferable cron, since app will go on Linux server on Linode or DigitalOcean; want to make sure that system continues to run when computer is asleep
  • Query into rows variable returns list of tuples.
# # Establish sqlite3 connection and cursor
# ___

cursor.execute("""
    SELECT symbol, company FROM stock
""")
rows = cursor.fetchall() # Fetch results of query; returns list of tuples
for row in rows: 
    print(row)
  • To obtain dictionaries instead of tuples, modify sqlite3 connection.
  • General idea for below: Get new symbols only without repeating old ones, allows for redundancy to be reduced.
import sqlite3 
import alpaca_trade_api as tradeapi 
connection = sqlite3.connect("app.db") # Connect to database
connection.row_factory = sqlite3.Row # To get dictionaries instead of tuples
cursor = connection.cursor() # To execute SQL statements

cursor.execute("""
    SELECT symbol, company FROM stock
""")
rows = cursor.fetchall() # Fetch results of query; returns list of tuples
symbols = [row["symbol"] for row in rows] # Get list of symbols

api = tradeapi.REST("PKQYMTPLLLFNOKD1MJQD", "NgfFNpdX7RtH5arzNDgGcYuwjU20dNqHUV8jhMdG", base_url = "https://paper-api.alpaca.markets") # Replace insert_api_key_id and insert_api_secret
assets = api.list_assets() # Return list of symbols
for asset in assets: 
    # print(asset)
    try: 
        if (asset.status == "active") and (asset.tradable) and (asset.symbol not in symbols): # To avoid overlaps with inactive ones; want only info of interest
            print(f"Added a new stock {asset.symbol} {asset.name}")
            cursor.execute("INSERT INTO stock (symbol, company) VALUES (?, ?)", (asset.symbol, asset.name))
    except Exception as e: 
        print(asset.symbol) # symbol was set to be unique
        print(e)
  • https://crontab.guru to create cron job expressions with easy interpretation.
  • Goal: 0th minute of 22nd hour (Every day at 2200)
    • crontab -e in terminal to open up crontab
    • s to start editing
    • :wq to quit and save
    • ls -al in terminal to see functions run in home directory
  • Creating time for function to automatically run:
    • cron time (This case: 0 22 * * *)
    • Location of Python (This case (for Mac): /usr/bin/python3)
    • Location of Python file to run (This case: /Users/student/Documents\ \ SNG058/Self-Learning/Algo\ Trading\ Models/Stock\ Trading\ App\ Tutorial/populate_db.py)
    • Log creation (">>" redirects print statements to log, verifies if program is running consistently, checks for exceptions (This case: >> /Users/student/Documents\ \ SNG058/Self-Learning/Algo\ Trading\ Models/Stock\ Trading\ App\ Tutorial/populate.log 2>&1)
  • By default uses directory cron is in; change connection to be absolute path to minimise confusion.
    • NOTE: For sqlite3.connect(path) to work, path must not have ANY spaces in it.
0 22 * * * /usr/bin/python3 /Users/student/Documents\ \ SNG058/Self-Learning/Algo\ Trading\ Models/Stock\ Trading\ App\ Tutorial/populate_db.py >> /Users/student/Documents\ \ SNG058/Self-Learning/Algo\ Trading\ Models/Stock\ Trading\ App\ Tutorial/populate.log 2>&1

Intraday price data (OPTIONAL)

  • If day trading on shorter timeframe, would be more interested in shorter term price movements.
  • Alpace Market Data API allows for data retrieval for timeframes of 1 min, 5 min, 15 min.
  • Limitations
    • API does not contain all data for every exchange in free version, will likely need premium for every minute.

Polygon.io (OPTIONAL)

  • Alpaca with brokerage account (REQUIRES PAYMENT) allows access to Polygon.io data with Alpaca API key.
  • Polygon has data from all US exchanges, its API is integrated to Alpaca Trade API library.
  • To use the Alpaca Polygon integration, call api.polygon.historic_agg_v2() to get bars aggregated on desired timeframe.
  • Example: Retrieve Zillow stock prices for hourly, 5 minute and 1 minute timeframes -> Data is more granular.
api = tradeapi.REST(config.API_KEY, config.SECRET_KEY, base_url = config.API_URL)

hourly_bars = api.polygon.historic_agg_v2("Z", 1, "hour", _from = "2020-10-02", to = "2020-10-22")
five_minute_bars = api.polygon.historic_agg_v2("Z", 5, "minute", _from = "2020-10-02", to = "2020-10-22")
minute_bars = api.polygon.historic_agg_v2("Z", 1, "minute", _from = "2020-10-02", to = "2020-10-22")

for bar in hourly_bars: 
    print(bar.timestamp, bar.open, bar.high, bar.low, bar.close, bar.volume)

for bar in five_minute_bars: 
    print(bar.timestamp, bar.open, bar.high, bar.low, bar.close, bar.volume)

for bar in minute_bars: 
    print(bar.timestamp, bar.open, bar.high, bar.low, bar.close, bar.volume)

Database changes

  • stock_id is integer connecting to id, since symbol is not necessarily unique due to changing or getting delisted (and thus becoming available for another stock) over time.
  • adjusted_volume from stock_price table is unnecessary.
  • company from stock is not necessarily correct due to ETFs.
  • Could either use ALTER TABLE or DROP TABLE with recreation.
  • For now will create drop_tables.py
import config 
import sqlite3 
connection = sqlite3.connect(config.DB_FILE) # Connect to database
cursor = connection.cursor() # To execute SQL statements

cursor.executescript("""
    DROP TABLE stock_price;
    DROP TABLE stock;
""")
connection.commit() # To commit changes to databases
  • Adjust values accordingly in create_db.py and populate_db.py (now named populate_stocks.py)

Populating stock price table

  • Alpaca API can only fetch stock data for 200 symbols max at a time, try to loop through stock symbols in chunks of 200.
  • Need to change data selection to exclude any symbols with "/" in them.
import config 
import sqlite3 
import alpaca_trade_api as tradeapi 
from alpaca_trade_api.rest import TimeFrame
import datetime as dt
import pytz

connection = sqlite3.connect(config.DB_FILE) # Connect to database
connection.row_factory = sqlite3.Row # To get dictionaries instead of tuples
cursor = connection.cursor() # To execute SQL statements

# cursor.execute("""
#     SELECT id, symbol, name FROM stock
# """) # Need to account for alpaca_trade_api.rest.APIError: invalid symbol: BCH/USD
cursor.execute("""
    SELECT id, symbol, name FROM stock WHERE symbol NOT LIKE ("%/%")
""")
rows = cursor.fetchall() # Fetch results of query; returns list of tuples
symbols = [row["symbol"] for row in rows] # Get list of symbols

# symbols = []
stock_dict = {} # Easy access of symbol and corresponding id
for row in rows: 
    symbol = row["symbol"]
    symbols.append(symbol) 
    stock_dict[symbol] = row["id"]

api = tradeapi.REST(config.API_KEY, config.SECRET_KEY, base_url = config.API_URL, api_version = "v2") # config.py variables 

timeNow = dt.datetime.now(pytz.timezone('US/Eastern'))
oneDayAgo = (timeNow - dt.timedelta(days=1)).strftime('%Y-%m-%d')

chunk_size = 200 # Iterate over data, 200 at a time
for i in range(0, len(symbols), chunk_size):
    symbol_chunk = symbols[i:i+chunk_size]

    barsets = api.get_bars(symbol_chunk, TimeFrame.Day, start = oneDayAgo, end = oneDayAgo, limit = 1)._raw # Results not guranteed
    # barsets = api.get_bars(symbol_chunk,TimeFrame.Day,"2022-03-31", "2022-03-31")._raw

    for bar in barsets: # Loop through each bar in barset
        symbol = bar["S"]
        print(f"processing symbol {symbol}")
        # print(bar)
        stock_id = stock_dict[symbol]
        cursor.execute("""
        INSERT INTO stock_price (stock_id, date, open, high, low, close, volume)
        VALUES (?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?, ?)
        """, (stock_id, bar["t"], bar["o"], bar["h"], bar["l"], bar["c"], bar["v"]))

connection.commit() # To commit changes to databases

Part 6: FastAPI Web UI

  • FastAPI to allow user-friendly access to data.
  • Install with pip3 install fastapi uvicorn.
    • fastapi is framework.
    • uvicorn is web server.
  • Create new FastAPI application main.py, then create basic route.
  • Sample FastAPI
    • Enter Uvicorn server with uvicorn main:app --reload.
    • Quit with CTRL + C
    • By default, will return JSON format, since FastAPI() is built for API backends by default.
    • "/" is base route
from fastapi import FastAPI 
app = FastAPI() 

@app.get("/")
def index(): 
    return {"Hello", "World"} 

@app.get("/hello")
def index(): 
    return {"Hello", "There"}
  • Want to create listing of stock symbols and stock pricings.
  • Do initial set up of connections as per usual into index().
  • Allows access to price data for users.
  • Below will return massive list of stock data due to rows
import config 
import sqlite3 
from fastapi import FastAPI 

app = FastAPI() 

@app.get("/")
def index(): 
    connection = sqlite3.connect(config.DB_FILE) # Connect to database
    connection.row_factory = sqlite3.Row # To get dictionaries instead of tuples
    cursor = connection.cursor() # To execute SQL statements
    cursor.execute("""
        SELECT id, symbol, name FROM stock
    """)
    rows = cursor.fetchall() # Fetch results of query; returns list of tuples
    return {"title": "Dashboard", "stocks": rows}

Templates (https://fastapi.tiangolo.com/advanced/templates/)

  • Want to return templates from this route.

  • Will use jinja2

    • Used by Flask.
    • Install with pip install jinja2.
    • Import with from fastapi.templating import Jinja2Templates.

  • Create templates object.

  • Declare Request parameter in the path operation that will return a template (Templates directory for display logic); create "templates" folder for such.

    • Reference made such that when user makes request to web page, request carries lots of information (e.g. http headers, IP address, browser used).
    • To be passed to template.

  • Return TemplateResponse, pass template name, the request object, and a "context" dictionary with key-value pairs to be used inside of the Jinja2 template.

  • main.py

import config 
import sqlite3 
from fastapi import FastAPI, Request # Part 1 
from fastapi.templating import Jinja2Templates # Part 1 

app = FastAPI() 
templates = Jinja2Templates(directory="templates") # Part 2

@app.get("/")
def index(request: Request): # Part 3
    connection = sqlite3.connect(config.DB_FILE) 
    connection.row_factory = sqlite3.Row 
    cursor = connection.cursor() 
    cursor.execute("""
        SELECT id, symbol, name FROM stock
    """)
    rows = cursor.fetchall() 
    return templates.TemplateResponse(
        request=request, name="index.html", context={"stocks": rows}
    ) # Part 4
  • index.html
    • {} to access stored data.
<html> 
    <head>
        <title>STONKS</title>
    </head>
    <body>

        <table>
            <tr>
                <td>{{ stock.id }}</td>
                <td>{{ stock.symbol }}</td>
                <td>{{ stock.name }}</td>
            </tr>
        </table>
        {% endfor %}
    </body>
</html>

UI framework

  • Semantic UI for default styling (https://semantic-ui.com).
  • Access CDN releases (https://semantic-ui.com/introduction/advanced-usage.html) into heading.
  • Formatting for table (https://semantic-ui.com/collections/table.html)
  • Mitigate table size with layouts.
  • Include header within div for alignment.
  • Want table ordered by symbols, with links based on stock to retrieve price data.
  • main.py
# ...
@app.get("/stock/{symbol}")
def index(request: Request, symbol): 
    connection = sqlite3.connect(config.DB_FILE) 
    connection.row_factory = sqlite3.Row 
    cursor = connection.cursor() 
    cursor.execute("""
        SELECT id, symbol, name FROM stock WHERE symbol = ?
    """, (symbol,))
    row = cursor.fetchone() 

    cursor.execute("""
        SELECT * FROM stock_price WHERE stock_id = ? ORDER BY date DESC
    """, (row["id"],)) # Get data from stock price data
    prices = cursor.fetchall() 

    return templates.TemplateResponse(
        request=request, name="stock_detail.html", context={"stock": row, "bars": prices}
    )
  • Common UI functionality into layout.html.
    • Access with {% extends "layout.html" %}.
    • Wrap content up with {% block content %} and {% endblock %}
